\section*{OSTEOPOROSIS}

It is a term used to refer to any condition that causes reduction in the mass of bone per unit volume. Most often is used to describe its primary type which is an age related metabolic bone disease in which there is severe reduction in the skeletal bone mass and increased susceptibility to fractures. In this case bone resorption occurs faster than bone formation i.e. osteoclastic activity is higher than the osteoblastic activity. It occurs mainly on the bones of the wrist, hip and vertebral column. It has two main types;-

\section*{Primary type}

This is postmenopausal osteoporosis and is the most common. It has association with underlying medical condition.

\section*{Secondary type}

Occurs with underlying medical condition e.g. hyperparathyroidism or an iatrogenic cause e.g. long term corticosteroid or heparin administration.

Risks factors of osteoporosis.
They are divided into two
I. Individual risk factors.
- Increased age
- Family history
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_06_11_e8692ea26dfb72f59229g-39.jpg?height=438&width=509&top_left_y=124&top_left_x=468)
- Female gender
- Low weight and body mass index.
- Estrogen deficiency or menopause.
- Calcitonin deficiency
- Hyperthyroidism
- High anticoagulant doses
- Coexisting medical conditions (e.g. celiac disease) and medications e.g. (corticosteroids).
II. Life style risk factors.
- Cigarette smoking/ heavy caffeine intake/ alcohol abuse
- Lack of weight bearing exercise.
- Lack of exposure to sunshine.
- Diet low in calcium and vitamin D

\section*{Pathophysiology}

Normally through out a lifespan new bone is formed (osteoblastic activity) while old bone is resorbed (osteoclastic). The peak bone mass is at the age of 30-35 years of age. After this there is a decrease in calcium deposition and osteoblastic activity with age. This coupled with a decrease in estrogen production of menopause the end result is a decrease in bone mass and density. These bones become weak and prone to fractures

\section*{Clinical manifestations}
- Shortened stature
- Difficulties in bending
- Marked kyphosis of the thoracic spine (Dowager's hump)
- Back pain
- Proximal femur fractures especially of the femoral neck.
- Fracture of the distal radius

\section*{Management}

Intervention in the care of the client focuses on symptoms expressed. Important goals include
$\checkmark$ Adequate nutrition especially foods rich in calcium and vitamin D.
$\checkmark$ Exposure to sunlight to enable production of vitamin D.
