\section*{Bursitis and tendinitis}

They are inflammatory conditions that commonly occur in the shoulder. Buresae are fluid filled sacs that prevent friction between joint structures during joint activity. When inflamed they are painful. Similarly, muscle tendon sheaths became inflamed with repetitive stretching. The inflammation causes proliferation of synovial membrane and Pannus formation, which restricts joint movement.

\section*{Management}
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_06_11_e8692ea26dfb72f59229g-58.jpg?height=438&width=509&top_left_y=124&top_left_x=468)

\section*{ORTHOPEADIC NURSING}

Conservative treatment includes: - rest of extremity, intermittent ice and heat to the joint and NSAIDs to control the pain and inflammation.

\section*{Loose bodies}

They may occur in a joint as a result of articular cartilage wear and bone erosion, these fragments interfere with joint movement, locking the joint and cause painful movements. Loose bodies are removed by arthroscopic surgery.

\section*{Ganglion.}

It is a round firm projection, usually near the wrist. It is a collection of gelatinous material near the tendon sheaths and joints. It is caused by strains, contusions or a series or repeated minor strains as a result of which the tissues of the sheath or sac involved have gradually become weakened and distended. The ganglion is painless, but an affected joint is often weak and moderately painful secondary to local pressure.

\section*{Treatment}
- Aspiration or excision.
- Aspiration decompression may need to be repeated since fluid may accumulate.

\section*{Carpal tunnel syndrome}

It is an entrapment neuropathy caused by pressure from a thickened flexor tendon sheath, skeletal encroachment or soft tissue mass on the median nerve at the wrist.

Signs and symptoms
Numbness, pain, paresthesia and possible weakness along the median nerve (thumb, first and second fingers)

\section*{Management}
- Rest splint
- Avoidance of work that requires flexion of the wrist may relieve the symptoms.
- Surgical release of the transverse carpal ligament may be necessary.

\section*{Dupuytren's contracture.}

It is a slowly progressive contracture of the palmer fascia causing flexion of the little finger, the ring finger and frequently the middle fingers; which renders them more or less useless.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_06_11_e8692ea26dfb72f59229g-59.jpg?height=438&width=509&top_left_y=124&top_left_x=468)

\section*{ORTHOPEADIC NURSING}

It starts as thickening of the palmer fascia. The fibrous thickening extends to involve the skin in the distal palm and produces a contracture of the finger to which the palmer fascia is inserted.

\section*{Risk factors}
- People of Scandinavian or Northern European ancestry; it has been called the "Viking disease" or "Celtic hand", though it is also widespread in some Mediterranean countries (e.g., Spain and Bosnia) and in Japan;
- Men rather than women (men are ten times as likely to develop the condition);
- People over the age of 40;
- People with a family history ( $60 \%$ to $70 \%$ of those afflicted have a genetic predisposition to Dupuytren's contracture);
- People with liver cirrhosis.
- Some suspected, but unproven, causes of Dupuytren's contracture include trauma, diabetes, alcoholism, epilepsy therapy with phenytoin, and liver disease.

\section*{Tennis elbow}

It is a painful condition that is due to excessive pronation and supination activities of the forearm. The pain characteristically radiates down the extensor surface of the forearm.

\section*{READ AND MAKE NOTE ON FOOT DEFORMITIES}

\section*{BONE TUMORS}

Bone tumors occur commonly in children and adolescents but less common in older adults.
- In older adults is most commonly the result of metastatic spread from another tumor.
- Characterized by rapid metastasis \& bone destruction
- Common indication for amputation
- There are many different types of bone cancer, The most common primary bone tumors include osteosarcoma, Ewing's sarcoma, chondrosarcoma, malignant fibrous histiocytoma, fibrosarcoma, and chordoma.
- There are various types of benign bone tumors. These include osteoid osteoma, osteoblastoma, osteochondroma, enchondroma, chondromyxoid fibroma, aneurysmal bone cyst, unicameral bone cyst, and giant cell tumor (which has the potential to become malignant). As with other types of benign tumors, these are not cancerous.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_06_11_e8692ea26dfb72f59229g-60.jpg?height=438&width=509&top_left_y=124&top_left_x=468)

\section*{ORTHOPEADIC NURSING}

Two other relatively common types of cancer than develop in the bones: lymphoma and multiple myeloma
- Osteosarcoma:-_most common primary malignant bone cancer. Commonly affects males between 10-25 years old but can attack older adults even. It often occurs in the long bones of the arms and legs at areas of rapid growth around the knees and shoulders of children. This type of cancer is often very aggressive with risk of spread to the lungs. The five-year survival rate is about $65 \%$.
- Ewing's sarcoma:- is the most aggressive bone tumor and affects younger people between 4-15 years of age. It is more common in males and is very rare in people over 30 years of age. It most commonly occurs in the middle of the long bones of the arms and legs. The three-year survival rate is about $65 \%$, but this rate is much lower if there has been spread to the lungs or other tissues of the body.
- Chondrosarcoma:- is the second most common bone tumor and accounts for about $25 \%$ of all malignant bone tumors. These tumors arise from the cartilage cells and can either be very aggressive or relatively slow growing. Unlike many other bone tumors, chondrosarcoma is most common in people over 40 years of age. It is slightly more common in males and can potentially spread to the lungs and lymph nodes. Chondrosarcoma most commonly affects the bones of the pelvis and hips. The five-year survival for the aggressive form is about $30 \%$, but the survival rate for slow-growing tumors is $90 \%$.
- Malignant fibrous histiocytoma (MFH):- affects the soft tissues, including muscle, ligaments, tendons, and fat. It is the most common soft-tissue malignancy in later adult life, usually occurring in people 50-60 years of age. It most commonly affects the extremities and is about twice as common in males as females. MFH also has a wide range of severity. The overall five-year survival rate is about $35 \%-60 \%$.
- Fibrosarcoma:- is much more rare than the other bone tumors. It is most common in people 35-55 years of age. It most commonly affects the soft tissues of the leg behind the knee. Slightly more common in males
- Chordoma :- is a very rare tumor with an average survival of about six years after diagnosis. It occurs in adults over 30 years of age and is about twice as common in males as females. It most commonly affects either the lower or upper end of the spinal column.
- Lymphoma, a cancer arising from the cells of the immune system, usually begins in the lymph nodes but can begin in the bone.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_06_11_e8692ea26dfb72f59229g-61.jpg?height=438&width=509&top_left_y=124&top_left_x=468)
- Multiple myeloma begins in the bones, but it is not usually considered a bone tumor because it is a tumor of the bone marrow cells and not of the bone cells.

\section*{Causes}
- Exposure to therapeutic radiations but not other radiations
- Genetic influences \& familial tendencies
- Hormonal imbalances \& growth spurts
- Adults with hyperparathyroidism, paget's and chronic osteomyelitis
- Trauma and sites of old bone infarcts or fractures
- Multiple exostoses (overgrowth of bone tissue)
- Benign bone tumors and bone marrow transplants
- Treatment with some chemotherapeutic drugs
- Young age (risk factor)

\section*{Clinical features}
- Pain:- In most cases, the symptoms become gradually more severe with time. Initially, the pain may only be present either at night or with activity. Depending on the growth of the tumor, those affected may have symptoms for weeks, months, or years before seeking medical advice.
- In some cases, a mass or lump may be felt either on the bone or in the tissues surrounding the bone. This is most common with MFH or fibrosarcoma but can occur with other bone tumors.
- The bones can become weakened by the tumor and lead to a fracture after little or no trauma or just from standing on the affected bone. This can occur with both benign and malignant tumors. Even benign tumors can spread locally and weaken the surrounding bone.
- If the tumor compresses the surrounding nerve it can cause pain, numbness, or tingling in the extremities.
- If the surrounding blood vessels are compressed, it can affect the blood flow to the extremities.
- Fever, chills, night sweats, and weight loss can occur but are less common. These symptoms are more common after spread of the tumor to other tissues in the body.

\section*{Diagnosis}
- Take a complete medical history:- gives clues on diagnosis. Some types of cancer have familial tendency while others are more common in people with certain lifestyles e.g. smoking.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_06_11_e8692ea26dfb72f59229g-62.jpg?height=438&width=509&top_left_y=124&top_left_x=468)

\section*{ORTHOPEADIC NURSING}
- A complete physical examination to include testing the muscle strength, sensation to touch, and reflexes to help find the cause of the symptoms
- Certain blood tests can be ordered that can help to identify a possible cancer.
- Imaging studies:- to help determine the type of cancer or to identify if a fracture has occurred or if the bone has been weakened and is at risk for a potential fracture.
- C.T Scan:-gives cross-sectional images, is better able to identify a possible tumor and gives additional information on the size and location of the tumor.
- M.R.Is:- provides cross sectional imaging of the body. It provides better detail of the soft tissues, including muscles, tendons, ligaments, nerves, and blood vessels than a CT scan. This test can give better detail on whether or not the bone tumor has broken through the bone and involved the surrounding soft tissues or not.
- A bone scan:-_identifies areas of rapidly growing or remodeling bone $\&$ is often taken of the entire body. It may be ordered to identify any other areas of bone involvement throughout the body. It is not specific for any specific type of tumor and can be positive with many other conditions including infection, fracture, and arthritis.
- Biopsy of a sample of the tumor:- the biopsy can be obtained either through a needle biopsy or incision biopsy. Imaging studies will be used to determine the safest and easiest location of biopsy

\section*{Management}
- The best treatment is based on:-
$\checkmark$ The type of bone cancer.
$\checkmark$ The location of the cancer.
$\checkmark$ How aggressive the cancer is.
$\checkmark$ Whether or not the cancer has metastasized or not

\section*{Main types of treatment}
- Surgery
- Chemotherapy
- Radiation therapy
N.B These can be used either individually or combined with each other.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_06_11_e8692ea26dfb72f59229g-63.jpg?height=438&width=509&top_left_y=124&top_left_x=468)

\section*{Surgery}
- The goal of surgery is usually to remove the entire tumor and a surrounding area of normal bone.
- Historically amputations were frequently used to remove bone cancer.
- In many cases, the tumor can be removed with a rim of normal bone without the need for an amputation.
- Depending on the amount of bone removed, the surgeon will replace something in its location. For smaller areas, this may be either bone cement or a bone graft from another place in your body or from the bone bank. For larger areas, the surgeon may place larger grafts from the bone bank or metal implants. Some of these metal implants have the ability to lengthen when used in growing children.

\section*{Chemotherapy}
- This is the use of various medications used to try to stop the growth of the cancer cells.
- Chemotherapy can be used prior to surgery to try to shrink the bone tumor to make surgery easier.
- It can also be used after surgery to try to kill any remaining cancer cells left following surgery.

\section*{Radiation}
- Uses high-energy X-ray aimed at the site of the cancer to try to kill the cancer cells. This Rx is given in small doses daily over a period of days to months. As with chemotherapy, radiation therapy can be used either before or after a potential surgery, depending on the specific type of cancer.
- Bone marrow transplant

\section*{AMPUTATION}

It is the removal of a body extremity by trauma or surgery.

\section*{Indications}
1. Peripheral vascular disease:- due to diabetes mellitus causing arterial occlusion
2. Gangrene: - from other causes
3. Neoplasms:- Melanomas or Cancerous bone or soft tissue tumors e.g. osteosarcoma, osteochondroma, fibrosarcoma
4. Trauma:- Severe limb injuries e.g. burns, frost bites, Traumatic amputation or Amputation in utero by amniotic bands
5. Deformities:- affecting the digits and/or limbs or extra digits and/or limbs (e.g. polydactyly)
6. Infection:- Bone infection (osteomyelitis)
