\section*{Complications.}
* Hemorrhage: - this is because the major blood vessels have been disturbed.
* Infection: - risk for infection increases with contaminated wound after traumatic amputation.
* Skin breakdown: - caused by the prosthesis.
* Phantom limb pain: - caused by serving of peripheral nerves.
* Joint contracture: - caused by positioning and protective flexion withdraw pattern associated with pain and muscle imbalance.

\section*{Nursing interventions for the complications.}

Hemorrhage: - monitor the patient for any signs or symptoms of bleeding.
Monitor the patient's vital signs and observe the sunction drainage.
Infection: - administer antibiotics as prescribed.
Monitor the incision, dressing and drainage for indications of infection e.g. change in Color, odor, or consistency of drainage, increasing discomfort.

Monitor for systemic indicators of infection e.g. elevated temperature and prompt report to the surgeon.
Phantom limb pain: - it is more frequently in above knee amputation. The patient describes pain Or unusual sensations such as numbness tingling or muscle cramps as well as a feeling that the extremity is present, crushed cramped or twisted in an abnormal Position. Since the pathogenesis of the phantom limb is unknown.
$\boldsymbol{-}$ Keeping the patient active helps decrease the occurrence of phantom limb pain.
* Early intensive rehabilitation and stump desensitization with kneading massage brings relief.
$\boldsymbol{+}$ Distraction technique and activity are helpful.
* Transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation (TENS) or local anesthetic may provide relief for some patients.
* Beta blockers may relief dull, burning discomfort, anti seizure may Control stabbing and cramping pain. Tricyclic antidepressant may improve mood or coping ability.

